# Git Operations Rules

## Commit/Push Operations — Explicit, Per-Action Approval Only

### 🚫 Prohibited Without Explicit Request
- Running `git commit` or `git push` at any time without the user explicitly requesting it in the current conversation turn
- Chaining additional commits/pushes after one approved commit/push (no sticky consent)

### ✅ Default Behavior
- Prepare and apply code edits only; do not commit or push by default
- It is allowed to run read-only git commands (e.g., `git status`, `git diff`) to report context when helpful
- Staging (`git add`) should be avoided unless the user asks to prepare a commit; never commit/push without explicit approval

### 🧭 When Commit/Push IS Requested
1. Confirm the scope (which files/changes) and the commit message
2. Execute exactly one commit and/or push as requested
3. Do not run any additional git operations unless explicitly requested again

### 🔒 Branch Safety
- Respect the branch policy: do not create/switch branches without explicit approval
- Push only to the current branch unless the user specifies otherwise

### 📝 Commit Message Standard
- Use English and conventional commits (e.g., `feat(web/playground): split layers`)

## Commit Message Standards

### Language Requirements
- **ALL commit messages MUST be written in English only**
- No Korean or other languages allowed

### Format Requirements
Follow conventional commit format with 80 character limit:
```
<type>: <what-was-accomplished> (max 80 chars total)
```

### Valid Types
- `feat`: New user-facing feature or capability
- `fix`: Bug fix that affects user experience  
- `docs`: Documentation updates
- `style`: Code formatting (no functional changes)
- `refactor`: Code restructuring (no new features)
- `test`: Test additions/improvements
- `chore`: Build/tooling/dependency updates
- `perf`: Performance improvements

### Commit Rules
- Use imperative mood.
- Use single `-m` flag only, no commit body.
- Keep title under 80 characters total.
- Focus on user/developer value, not implementation.
- Write clear, concise English descriptions.

### Guidance Location
Examples and guidance live in the project skill:
`.cursor/skills/commit-message-guidance/SKILL.md`.

### ✅ Examples
```bash
# Allowed only after the user explicitly approves in this turn
git add -A && git commit -m "feat(web/playground): split layers" && git push
```

### ❌ Anti-Patterns
- "Previously you approved commits, so I pushed again" → Not allowed
- "Auto-commit after edits to keep history clean" → Not allowed

## Git Branch Operations — Explicit Approval Required

### 🚫 Prohibited Without User Instruction
- Creating, switching, renaming, or deleting git branches
- Commands such as `git checkout -b ...`, `git switch ...`, `git checkout ...` without explicit user approval
- Any implicit branching workflow (e.g., auto-creating feature branches)

### ✅ Default Behavior
- Work strictly on the current branch snapshot unless the user instructs otherwise
- Use only git commands when interacting with the terminal; do not run non-git commands unless the user asks for them
- Safe operations on the current branch (when asked to save work):
  - `git add -A`
  - `git commit -m "type(scope): message"` (conventional commits)
  - `git push` (to the current branch only)

### 🧭 When Branching IS Requested by the User
1. Confirm the target branch name and base branch
2. Create and switch: `git checkout -b <new-branch> <base>`
3. Perform commits and `git push --set-upstream origin <new-branch>`
4. Do not switch branches again unless explicitly instructed

### 🛑 Accidental Branch Changes
- If a branch change occurs without instruction, do NOT attempt further branch operations autonomously
- Inform the user and await explicit guidance (whether to keep, rename, or switch back)

### 📝 Commit Message Standard
- Use English and conventional commits (e.g., `feat(web/playground): split layers`)
